definition.value: Treatment with agent to increase urine flow in patients with an enlarged prostate.
Treatment with agents used to reduce the absorption of dietary phosphate
Treatments that are anti-inflammatory and immunosuppressive.
Treatment with an agent or medication that regulates hormones released by the pituitary.
Treatment with an agent regulating protaglandins.
Treatment with any agent or medication that modifies androgen, estrogens, and/or progestogens.
Use of any agent that can alter hormone levels or modulate hormone effects.
Treatment with an agent or medication that regulates hormones released by the thyroid.
Use of a compound which stimulates anabolism and inhibits catabolism. Anabolic agents stimulate the development of muscle mass, strength, and power.
Treatment with an agent to modify androgen action.
A drug which acts to modulates estrogenic activity in the body, either by modulating the amount of estrogen or by modulating the activity of whatever estrogen is present.
Treatment with an agent to modify progestin action.
Treatment with an agent to that selectively modifies estrogen receptor action.
Use of a drug to treat hyperparathyroidism by reducing the excessive production of parathyroid hormones.
Use of a compound which increases or activates the biosynthesis or actions of androgens.
Use of a compound which inhibits or antagonizes the biosynthesis or actions of androgens.
Treatment with an agent or medication that stimulates hormones released by the thyroid.
Use of a drug to treat hyperthyroidism by reducing the excessive production of thyroid hormones.
Use of a drug that induces, enhances, restores or suppresses the host's immune system, or an agent that utilizes or is derived from a component of the immune system.
Use of a substance that augments, stimulates, activates, potentiates, or modulates the immune response at either the cellular or humoral level.

value.value: A classical agent (Freund's adjuvant, BCG, Corynebacterium parvum, et al.) contains bacterial antigens. It could also be endogenous (e.g., histamine, interferon, transfer factor, tuftsin, interleukin-1). Its mode of action is either non-specific, resulting in increased immune responsiveness to a wide variety of antigens, or antigen-specific, i.e., affecting a restricted type of immune response to a narrow group of antigens. The therapeutic efficacy is related to its antigen-specific immunoadjuvanticity.

definition.value: Use of an agent that suppresses immune function by one of several mechanisms of action.

value.value: Classical cytotoxic immunosuppressants act by inhibiting DNA synthesis. Others may act through activation of T-cells or by inhibiting the activation of helper cells. In addition, an immunosuppressive agent is a role played by a compound which is exhibited by a capability to diminish the extent and/or voracity of an immune response.

definition.value: Treatment with antibodies to a disease to provide a temporary immunity.

value.value:
The drug treatment of inflammatory bowel disease (IBD), which may include the use of anti-inflammatory agents and
agents that reduce the symptoms associated with IBD.
The salts or esters of salicylic acids, or salicylate esters of an organic acid. Some of these have analgesic, antipyretic, and anti-inflammatory activities by inhibiting prostaglandin synthesis.

definition.value: Treatment with drug or agent to treat or prevent deformities or abnormalities of the bone caused by a metabolic disorder.
Use of a drug to treat eye conditions or eye diseases.
Treatment with medication delivered directly to the eye to treat allergies or allergy symptoms.
Use of a drug which can be used to prevent or alleviate glaucoma, a disease in which the optic nerve is damaged, resulting in progressive, irreversible loss of vision.
Treatment with an agent or medication formulated to be applied in the eyes, to reduce pain or to treat inflammation, especially used after eye surgery to relieve pain.

label.value: ophthalmic prostaglandin and prostamide agent therapy

definition.value: Treatment with an agent applied directly to the eye to treat elevated intraocular pressure (IOP) via regulating prostaglandin and prostamide.
Treatment with a substance intended for administration either on the outer ear or into the auditory canal.

value.value: An agent that exerts a physiologic effect on any anatomic entity that is part of the respiratory tract and airways.

definition.value: Use of drugs that bind to but do not activate histamine receptors, thereby blocking the actions of histamine or histamine agonists.
Treatment with an inhaled agent that reduces inflammation and mucus in the airways that carry air to the lungs.
Use of a drug designed to prevent leukotriene synthesis or activity by blocking binding at the receptor level.
Use of an agent that causes an increase in the expansion of a bronchus or bronchial tubes.
Treatment with an agent that blocks the effect of acetylcholine in airways and nasal passages to keep the airways from constricting during asthma and allergy-related brathing issues.
Treatment with a phosphodiesterase (PDE) inhibitor that decreases mean pulmonary arterial pressure.
Treatment with an agent for reversible airway obstruction in diseases such as asthma and COPD. These agents produce bronchodilation by stimulating beta2 adrenergic receptors on airway smooth muscle.
Treatment with an agent that block mast cell degranulation, stabilizing the cell and thereby preventing the release of histamine and other factors thereby preventing or regulating allergic disorders.
Treatment with an agent that decreases pulmonary hypertension.

value.value: Treatment with a central nervous system depressant used to induce drowsiness or sleep or to reduce psychological excitement or anxiety.

definition.value: Use of a drug used to produce muscle relaxation (excepting neuromuscular blocking agents). Its primary clinical and therapeutic use is the treatment of muscle spasm and immobility associated with strains, sprains, and injuries of the back and, to a lesser degree, injuries to the neck. Also used for the treatment of a variety of clinical conditions that have in common only the presence of skeletal muscle hyperactivity, for example, the muscle spasms that can occur in multiple sclerosis.
Use of a substance for the prophylaxis or therapy of infectious diseases.
Removal and examination of tissue, cells, or fluids from head for the purpose of detecting or characterizing disease.
Removal and examination of tissue, cells, or fluids from abdomen for the purpose of detecting or characterizing disease.
Removal and examination of tissue, cells, or fluids from adipose for the purpose of detecting or characterizing disease.
Removal and examination of tissue, cells, or fluids from adrenal cortex for the purpose of detecting or characterizing disease.
Removal and examination of tissue, cells, or fluids from adrenal gland for the purpose of detecting or characterizing disease.
Removal and examination of tissue, cells, or fluids from anal canal for the purpose of detecting or characterizing disease.
